WEBVTT

p01
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.412
Three complaints, one shape.

p02
00:00:01.412 --> 00:00:03.363
Tickets stopped reaching Zoho.

p03
00:00:03.363 --> 00:00:05.626
Single sign-on users locked out.

p04
00:00:05.626 --> 00:00:08.173
An accounting export full of holes.

p05
00:00:08.173 --> 00:00:13.719
Each one is a connector that quit authenticating, and each gets the same read:

p06
00:00:13.719 --> 00:00:17.178
open the connector, check its status, check its token,

p07
00:00:17.178 --> 00:00:20.355
then look at the surface the user actually feels.

p08
00:00:20.894 --> 00:00:21.897
Open the connector. Settings, Integrations, Zoho Desk.

p09
00:00:22.727 --> 00:00:25.842
One chip is the headline: Not Configured, with a warning triangle.

p10
00:00:26.455 --> 00:00:30.307
In this demo tenant Zoho was never connected, so that reading is honest.

p11
00:00:30.731 --> 00:00:41.085
On a live tenant that chip is your first and fastest read, before you touch anything else.

p12
00:00:41.715 --> 00:00:43.889
Four tiles sit across the top of the card.

p13
00:00:44.656 --> 00:00:47.798
Connection reads Not set, which matches the banner.

p14
00:00:48.235 --> 00:00:49.651
Data center, US. Sync direction, both.

p15
00:00:50.019 --> 00:00:51.407
When a working connection drops, this row is the quick read

p16
00:00:52.297 --> 00:00:57.440
before you go digging through credentials.

p17
00:00:57.890 --> 00:00:59.251
Top right, two buttons.

p18
00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:03.254
Test Connection fires a live probe against the real integration.

p19
00:01:03.855 --> 00:01:06.180
Edit Configuration opens the credential form.

p20
00:01:06.623 --> 00:01:08.836
Both are admin actions on production.

p21
00:01:09.194 --> 00:01:11.647
You locate them so your escalation can name them,

p22
00:01:12.011 --> 00:01:14.668
and you never click either one from the demo tenant.

p23
00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:16.270
Now the Settings tab, and the credentials block.

p24
00:01:16.481 --> 00:01:17.641
Client ID, secret, tokens: all blank or not set here.

p25
00:01:18.323 --> 00:01:19.942
The field that matters most is token expiry.

p26
00:01:20.190 --> 00:01:20.832
A connector that worked yesterday and fails today usually has a lapsed token behind it.

p27
00:01:21.082 --> 00:01:22.753
Expiry in the past, access token gone.

p28
00:01:22.978 --> 00:01:37.799
The re-auth is an admin job, and none of these values ever goes into your ticket.

p29
00:01:38.329 --> 00:01:39.810
Two more reads before you leave.

p30
00:01:40.396 --> 00:01:42.765
Under General, Enabled says yes. Under Sync, the direction is both.

p31
00:01:43.500 --> 00:01:45.378
So nobody switched it off. The failure is authentication.

p32
00:01:45.708 --> 00:01:54.286
And the Instructions tab next door holds the reconnect procedure for the admin who runs it.

p33
00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:56.658
Symptom one, the help desk surface.

p34
00:01:56.658 --> 00:01:59.455
Open I-T and Support, then Help Desk Zoho.

p35
00:01:59.455 --> 00:02:02.312
The page loads, and it tells the truth.

p36
00:02:02.312 --> 00:02:08.443
Every ticket count reads as a dash, and the card in the middle says Zoho Desk not connected,

p37
00:02:08.443 --> 00:02:11.118
with a button routing back to Settings.

p38
00:02:11.118 --> 00:02:14.995
Dashes in a healthy frame point at the connector, not the page.

p39
00:02:14.995 --> 00:02:16.933
That is your ticket surface evidence.

p40
00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:18.359
Symptom two, single sign-on lockouts.

p41
00:02:18.585 --> 00:02:20.351
Open System Users, under Users and Security.

p42
00:02:20.718 --> 00:02:24.153
More than eight thousand accounts load here, and two columns carry this ticket.

p43
00:02:24.466 --> 00:02:28.475
S-S-O flags who signs in through the provider, plain yes or no chips.

p44
00:02:28.779 --> 00:02:36.418
Last login shows when each of them last got in.

p45
00:02:36.620 --> 00:02:39.889
When the provider drops, the yes rows are your outage list.

p46
00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:42.922
Symptom three, the accounting export.

p47
00:02:43.392 --> 00:02:47.749
Back in Integrations, the accounting connector reads exactly like Zoho did:

p48
00:02:48.068 --> 00:02:50.707
status chip, test button, token block.

p49
00:02:51.113 --> 00:02:53.843
Same read, same rules, same hands off.

p50
00:02:54.456 --> 00:02:57.822
And if the connection is fine but entries land under the wrong codes, that's GL Code mapping.

p51
00:02:58.193 --> 00:03:00.720
Different lesson.

p52
00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:02.991
One trap before you write anything up.

p53
00:03:03.472 --> 00:03:05.232
Pages have bad minutes.

p54
00:03:05.651 --> 00:03:13.414
A list that will not load, or a stray fetch error,

p55
00:03:13.643 --> 00:03:14.646
can be the app's own data service hiccuping, and neither one proves an integration is down.

p56
00:03:14.862 --> 00:03:17.439
Reload first. Then let the connector's status chip make the call.

p57
00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:19.196
Now the escalation.

p58
00:03:19.551 --> 00:03:20.860
Name the integration. Quote the status banner word for word.

p59
00:03:21.387 --> 00:03:23.415
Say whether an admin ran Test Connection and what it returned.

p60
00:03:23.939 --> 00:03:27.458
Give the failure window with timestamps.

p61
00:03:27.934 --> 00:03:35.497
And keep every token, secret, and masked value out of it. No exceptions.

p62
00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:37.219
That's the whole playbook.

p63
00:03:38.414 --> 00:03:39.953
Scope to one connector. Read the chip, then the token expiry.

p64
00:03:40.221 --> 00:03:42.431
Locate Test Connection and leave it alone.

p65
00:03:42.706 --> 00:03:45.068
Confirm the surface the user feels, rule out a transient fetch error,

p66
00:03:45.272 --> 00:03:51.854
and route a ticket an admin can act on.

p67
00:03:52.901 --> 00:03:55.920
Every screen stayed read-only, start to finish.

